Section 1:
1 L.D. 186
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 ENERGY, UTILITIES AND TECHNOLOGY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 119, L.D. 186, “An Act to Clarify the
10 Public Utilities Commission's Authority to Establish Time-of-use Pricing for Standard-
11 offer Service”
12 Amend the bill by inserting after section 2 the following:
13 'Sec. 3. Public Utilities Commission; time-of-use rates updates. The Public
14 Utilities Commission shall submit a report to the joint standing committee of the
15 Legislature having jurisdiction over utilities and energy matters that describes the process
16 for participation in a commission proceeding and includes any other relevant information
17 as determined by the commission:
18 1. Upon issuance of a report, if a report is issued, in Public Utilities Commission
19 Docket No. 2024-00231; and
20 2. Prior to the initiation of an adjudicatory proceeding to establish time-of-use rates for
21 the provision of standard-offer service pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 35-A,
22 section 3212.
23 If the Public Utilities Commission submits a report in accordance with subsection 2
24 prior to the initiation of an adjudicatory proceeding to establish time-of-use rates for the
25 provision of standard-offer service, the report must include a description of how the Public
26 Utilities Commission will consider the potential effects of time-of-use rates on the types of
27 residential customers described in section 4.
28 Sec. 4. Considerations; time-of-use rates proceeding. In an adjudicatory
29 proceeding to establish time-of-use rates for the provision of standard-offer service
30 pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 35-A, section 3212, the Public Utilities
31 Commission shall consider the impact of time-of-use rates and seek to avoid negative
32 impacts of time-of-use rates on:
33 1. Residential customers who rely on life support systems;
Page 1 - 132LR0596(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 119, L.D. 186
1 2. Residential customers who receive assistance from the State due to a medical
2 condition and are participants in Central Maine Power's Electricity Lifeline Program or
3 Versant Power's LifeLight Program or successor programs;
4 3. Residential customers who are senior citizens; and
5 4. Economically vulnerable residential customers.'
6 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
7 number to read consecutively.
8 SUMMARY
99 This amendment adds 2 additional sections to the bill to require that the Public Utilities
1100 Commission submit a report to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having
1111 jurisdiction over utilities and energy matters upon the issuance of a report in a commission
1122 docket related to time-of-use rates and prior to the initiation of an adjudicatory proceeding
1133 to establish time-of-use rates for the provision of standard-offer service in accordance with
1144 the provisions of the bill. It also directs the commission, in such an adjudicatory
1155 proceeding, to consider the impact of time-of-use rates and seek to avoid the negative
1166 impacts of such rates on certain residential customers.
1177 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
1188 (See attached)
Page 2 - 132LR0596(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
